Strengths of weak ties
>In 1970, Dr. Granovetter surveyed 282 white-collar men living in a suburb of Boston, USA, to determine how they obtained information that helped them find jobs. He found that 16% of those surveyed obtained jobs through information from people they met frequently, i.e., those with strong social ties, while the remaining 84% obtained jobs through information from people they met infrequently, i.e., those with weak social ties. The study also revealed that those who obtained jobs through information from such "[weak ties]" had greater [satisfaction].
